To generate a table of contents (ToC) automatically in a LaTeX document, you can follow this example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Packages used for formatting and improving the appearance of the ToC
\usepackage{tocloft} % For customizing the ToC
\usepackage{titlesec} % For customizing section formatting

% Customize the appearance of the ToC (optional)
\renewcommand{\cftsecpresnum}{\bfseries} % Bold section numbers
\renewcommand{\cftsubsecpresnum}{\bfseries\hspace{0em}} % Bold subsection numbers with no extra space

% Customize the appearance of section and subsection titles (optional)
\titleformat{\section}{\Large\bfseries}{\thesection}{1em}{}{}
\titleformat{\subsection}{\large\bfseries}{\thesubsection}{1em}{}{}

\begin{document}

% Title of the document (optional)
\title{Example Document}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle

% Generate the table of contents
\tableofcontents

% Main content
\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Background}
This is the background subsection.

\subsection{Purpose}
This is the purpose subsection.

\section{Main Body}
This is the main body section.

\subsection{First Topic}
This is the first topic subsection.

\subsection{Second Topic}
This is the second topic subsection.

\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\documentclass{article}` is used to define the document class as an article. The `\usepackage{tocloft}` and `\usepackage{titlesec}` packages are imported to customize the appearance of the table of contents and section headings.

The `\renewcommand{\cftsecpresnum}{\bfseries}` and `\renewcommand{\cftsubsecpresnum}{\bfseries\hspace{0em}}` commands are used to make section and subsection numbers bold in the ToC, with no extra space before subsection numbers.

`\titleformat` commands are used to customize the appearance of section and subsection headings. In this case, we made them bold and adjusted the spacing.

The `\maketitle` command generates the title page if you provide a title, author, and date. The `\tableofcontents` command is placed where you want the table of contents to appear in the document.

The main content is organized using `\section` and `\subsection` commands, which are automatically included in the table of contents. When you compile this LaTeX document, a table of contents will be generated based on the sections and subsections, with appropriate page numbers.

